# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: boosting-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] AdaBoost is adaptive in the sense that subsequent weak learners (models) are adjusted in favor of instances misclassified by previous models.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] In some problems, it can be less susceptible to overfitting than other learning algorithms.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] The individual learners can be weak, but as long as the performance of each one is slightly better than random guessing, the final model can be proven to converge to a strong learner.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] Although AdaBoost is typically used to combine weak base learners (such as decision stumps), it has been shown to also effectively combine strong base learners (such as deeper decision trees), producing an even more accurate model.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] Every learning algorithm tends to suit some problem types better than others, and typically has many different parameters and configurations to adjust before it achieves optimal performance on a dataset.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] AdaBoost (with decision trees as the weak learners) is often referred to as the best out-of-the-box classifier.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] When used with decision tree learning, information gathered at each stage of the AdaBoost algorithm about the relative 'hardness' of each training sample is fed into the tree-growing algorithm such that later trees tend to focus on harder-to-classify examples.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] AdaBoost refers to a particular method of training a boosted classifier.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] A boosted classifier is a classifier of the form $F_{T}(x)=\sum _{t=1}^{T}f_{t}(x)$ where each $f_{t}$ is a weak learner that takes an object x as input and returns a value indicating the class of the object.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] For example, in the two-class problem, the sign of the weak learner's output identifies the predicted object class and the absolute value gives the confidence in that classification.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] Each weak learner produces an output hypothesis h which fixes a prediction $h(x_{i})$ for each sample in the training set.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] At each iteration t , a weak learner is selected and assigned a coefficient $\alpha _{t}$ such that the total training error $E_{t}$ of the resulting t -stage boosted classifier is minimized.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] Here $F_{t-1}(x)$ is the boosted classifier that has been built up to the previous stage of training and $f_{t}(x)=\alpha _{t}h(x)$ is the weak learner that is being considered for addition to the final classifier.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] At each iteration of the training process, a weight $w_{i,t}$ is assigned to each sample in the training set equal to the current error $E(F_{t-1}(x_{i}))$ on that sample.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] These weights can be used in the training of the weak learner.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] For instance, decision trees can be grown which favor the splitting of sets of samples with large weights.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] So it remains to determine which weak classifier is the best choice for $k_{m}$ , and what its weight $\alpha _{m}$ should be.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] Due to the convexity of E as a function of $\alpha _{m}$ , this new expression for $\alpha _{m}$ gives the global minimum of the loss function.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] Boosting is a form of linear regression in which the features of each sample $x_{i}$ are the outputs of some weak learner h applied to $x_{i}$ .
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] However, the exponential increase in the error for sample $x_{i}$ as $-y(x_{i})f(x_{i})$ increases, resulting in excessive weights being assigned to outliers.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] One feature of the choice of exponential error function is that the error of the final additive model is the product of the error of each stage, that is, $e^{\sum _{m}-y_{i}f_{m}(x_{i})}=\prod _{m}e^{-y_{i}f_{m}(x_{i})}$ .
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] Thus it can be seen that the weight update in the AdaBoost algorithm is equivalent to recalculating the error on $F_{t}(x)$ after each stage.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] There is a lot of flexibility allowed in the choice of loss function.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] As long as the loss function is monotonic and continuously differentiable, the classifier is always driven toward purer solutions.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] Boosting can be seen as minimization of a convex loss function over a convex set of functions.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] Thus AdaBoost algorithms perform either Cauchy (find $h(x)$ with the steepest gradient, choose $\alpha$ to minimize test error) or Newton (choose some target point, find $\alpha h(x)$ that brings $F_{t}$ closest to that point) optimization of training error.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] The output of decision trees is a class probability estimate $p(x)=P(y=1|x)$ , the probability that x is in the positive class.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] Thus, rather than multiplying the output of the entire tree by some fixed value, each leaf node is changed to output half the logit transform of its previous value.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] LogitBoost represents an application of established logistic regression techniques to the AdaBoost method.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] That is $z_{t}$ is the Newton–Raphson approximation of the minimizer of the log-likelihood error at stage t , and the weak learner $f_{t}$ is chosen as the learner that best approximates $z_{t}$ by weighted least squares.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] As p approaches either 1 or 0, the value of $p_{t}(x_{i})(1-p_{t}(x_{i}))$ becomes very small and the *z* term, which is large for misclassified samples, can become numerically unstable, due to machine precision rounding errors.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] While previous boosting algorithms choose $f_{t}$ greedily, minimizing the overall test error as much as possible at each step, GentleBoost features a bounded step size. $f_{t}$ is chosen to minimize ${\textstyle \sum _{i}w_{t,i}(y_{i}-f_{t}(x_{i}))^{2}}$ , and no further coefficient is applied.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] Thus, in the case where a weak learner exhibits perfect classification performance, GentleBoost chooses $f_{t}(x)=\alpha _{t}h_{t}(x)$ exactly equal to y , while steepest descent algorithms try to set $\alpha _{t}=\infty$ .
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] Empirical observations about the good performance of GentleBoost appear to back up Schapire and Singer's remark that allowing excessively large values of $\alpha$ can lead to poor generalization performance.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] If 50% of negative samples are filtered out by each stage, only a very small number of objects would pass through the entire classifier, reducing computation effort.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] This method has since been generalized, with a formula provided for choosing optimal thresholds at each stage to achieve some desired false positive and false negative rate.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] In the field of statistics, where AdaBoost is more commonly applied to problems of moderate dimensionality, early stopping is used as a strategy to reduce overfitting.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] For steepest descent versions of AdaBoost, where $\alpha _{t}$ is chosen at each layer *t* to minimize test error, the next layer added is said to be *maximally independent* of layer *t*: it is unlikely to choose a weak learner *t+1* that is similar to learner *t*.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] However, there remains the possibility that *t+1* produces similar information to some other earlier layer.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] Totally corrective algorithms, such as LPBoost, optimize the value of every coefficient after each step, such that new layers added are always maximally independent of every previous layer.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] This can be accomplished by backfitting, linear programming or some other method.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] Pruning is the process of removing poorly performing weak classifiers to improve memory and execution-time cost of the boosted classifier.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] The simplest methods, which can be particularly effective in conjunction with totally corrective training, are weight- or margin-trimming: when the coefficient, or the contribution to the total test error, of some weak classifier falls below a certain threshold, that classifier is dropped.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] Margineantu & Dietterich suggested an alternative criterion for trimming: weak classifiers should be selected such that the diversity of the ensemble is maximized.
[src:boosting-theory/adaboost] If two weak learners produce very similar outputs, efficiency can be improved by removing one of them and increasing the coefficient of the remaining weak learner.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] In machine learning (ML), **boosting** is an ensemble learning method that combines a set of less accurate models (called "weak learners") to create a single, highly accurate model (a "strong learner").
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Unlike other ensemble methods that build models in parallel (such as bagging), boosting algorithms build models sequentially.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Each new model in the sequence is trained to correct the errors made by its predecessors.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] This iterative process allows the overall model to improve its accuracy, particularly by reducing bias.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Boosting is a popular and effective technique used in supervised learning for both classification and regression tasks.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Robert Schapire's affirmative answer to this question in a 1990 paper led to the development of practical boosting algorithms.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] The first such algorithm was developed by Schapire, with Freund and Schapire later developing AdaBoost, which remains a foundational example of boosting.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] While boosting is not algorithmically constrained, most boosting algorithms consist of iteratively learning weak classifiers with respect to a distribution and adding them to a final strong classifier.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] When they are added, they are weighted in a way that is related to the weak learners' accuracy.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] After a weak learner is added, the data weights are readjusted, known as "re-weighting".
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Misclassified input data gain a higher weight and examples that are classified correctly lose weight.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Thus, future weak learners focus more on the examples that previous weak learners misclassified.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] The original ones, proposed by Robert Schapire (a recursive majority gate formulation), and Yoav Freund (boost by majority), were not adaptive and could not take full advantage of the weak learners.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Schapire and Freund then developed AdaBoost, an adaptive boosting algorithm that won the prestigious Gödel Prize.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Only algorithms that are provable boosting algorithms in the probably approximately correct learning formulation can accurately be called *boosting algorithms*.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Other algorithms that are similar in spirit to boosting algorithms are sometimes called "leveraging algorithms", although they are also sometimes incorrectly called boosting algorithms.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] The main variation between many boosting algorithms is their method of weighting training data points and hypotheses.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] AdaBoost is very popular and the most significant historically as it was the first algorithm that could adapt to the weak learners.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] It is often the basis of introductory coverage of boosting in university machine learning courses.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] There are many more recent algorithms such as LPBoost, TotalBoost, BrownBoost, xgboost, MadaBoost, LogitBoost, CatBoost and others.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Many boosting algorithms fit into the AnyBoost framework, which shows that boosting performs gradient descent in a function space using a convex cost function.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Given images containing various known objects in the world, a classifier can be learned from them to automatically classify the objects in future images.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Simple classifiers built based on some image feature of the object tend to be weak in categorization performance.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Using boosting methods for object categorization is a way to unify the weak classifiers in a special way to boost the overall ability of categorization.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Object categorization is a typical task of computer vision that involves determining whether or not an image contains some specific category of object.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] The idea is closely related with recognition, identification, and detection.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Appearance based object categorization typically contains feature extraction, learning a classifier, and applying the classifier to new examples.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] There are many ways to represent a category of objects, e.g. from shape analysis, bag of words models, or local descriptors such as SIFT, etc.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Examples of supervised classifiers are Naive Bayes classifiers, support vector machines, mixtures of Gaussians, and neural networks.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] However, research has shown that object categories and their locations in images can be discovered in an unsupervised manner as well.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] The recognition of object categories in images is a challenging problem in computer vision, especially when the number of categories is large.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] This is due to high intra class variability and the need for generalization across variations of objects within the same category.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Objects within one category may look quite different.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Even the same object may appear unalike under different viewpoint, scale, and illumination.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Background clutter and partial occlusion add difficulties to recognition as well.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Humans are able to recognize thousands of object types, whereas most of the existing object recognition systems are trained to recognize only a few, e.g. human faces, cars, simple objects, etc.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Research has been very active on dealing with more categories and enabling incremental additions of new categories, and although the general problem remains unsolved, several multi-category objects detectors (for up to hundreds or thousands of categories) have been developed.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] One means is by feature sharing and boosting.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] AdaBoost can be used for face detection as an example of binary categorization.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] The two categories are faces versus background.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] After boosting, a classifier constructed from 200 features could yield a 95% detection rate under a $10^{-5}$ false positive rate.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Another application of boosting for binary categorization is a system that detects pedestrians using patterns of motion and appearance.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] This work is the first to combine both motion information and appearance information as features to detect a walking person.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] It takes a similar approach to the Viola-Jones object detection framework.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Compared with binary categorization, multi-class categorization looks for common features that can be shared across the categories at the same time.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] They turn to be more generic edge like features.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] During learning, the detectors for each category can be trained jointly.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Compared with training separately, it generalizes better, needs less training data, and requires fewer features to achieve the same performance.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] The main flow of the algorithm is similar to the binary case.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] What is different is that a measure of the joint training error shall be defined in advance.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] During each iteration the algorithm chooses a classifier of a single feature (features that can be shared by more categories shall be encouraged).
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] This can be done via converting multi-class classification into a binary one (a set of categories versus the rest), or by introducing a penalty error from the categories that do not have the feature of the classifier.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] In the paper "Sharing visual features for multiclass and multiview object detection", A.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Torralba et al. used GentleBoost for boosting and showed that when training data is limited, learning via sharing features does a much better job than no sharing, given same boosting rounds.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Also, for a given performance level, the total number of features required (and therefore the run time cost of the classifier) for the feature sharing detectors, is observed to scale approximately logarithmically with the number of class, i.e., slower than linear growth in the non-sharing case.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Similar results are shown in the paper "Incremental learning of object detectors using a visual shape alphabet", yet the authors used AdaBoost for boosting.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Boosting algorithms can be based on convex or non-convex optimization algorithms.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] Convex algorithms, such as AdaBoost and LogitBoost, can be "defeated" by random noise such that they can't learn basic and learnable combinations of weak hypotheses.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] This limitation was pointed out by Long & Servedio in 2008.
[src:boosting-theory/boosting-machine-learning] However, by 2009, multiple authors demonstrated that boosting algorithms based on non-convex optimization, such as BrownBoost, can learn from noisy datasets and can specifically learn the underlying classifier of the Long–Servedio dataset.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] In statistics and machine learning, **ensemble methods** use multiple learning algorithms to obtain better predictive performance than could be obtained from any of the constituent learning algorithms alone.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Unlike a statistical ensemble in statistical mechanics, which is usually infinite, a machine learning ensemble consists of only a concrete finite set of alternative models, but typically allows for much more flexible structure to exist among those alternatives.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Supervised learning algorithms search through a hypothesis space to find a suitable hypothesis that will make good predictions with a particular problem.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Even if this space contains hypotheses that are very well-suited for a particular problem, it may be very difficult to find a good one.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Ensembles combine multiple hypotheses to form one which should be theoretically better.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Ensemble learning typically refers to bagging (bootstrap aggregating), boosting or stacking/blending techniques to induce high variance among the base models.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Bagging creates diversity by generating random samples from the training observations and fitting the same model to each different sample — also known as *homogeneous parallel ensembles*.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Boosting follows an iterative process by sequentially training each base model on the up-weighted errors of the previous base model, producing an additive model to reduce the final model errors — also known as *sequential ensemble learning*.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Stacking or blending consists of different base models, each trained independently (i.e. diverse/high variance) to be combined into the ensemble model — producing a *heterogeneous parallel ensemble*.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Common applications of ensemble learning include random forests (an extension of bagging), Boosted Tree models, and Gradient Boosted Tree Models.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Models in applications of stacking are generally more task-specific — such as combining clustering techniques with other parametric and/or non-parametric techniques.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Evaluating the prediction of an ensemble typically requires more computation than evaluating the prediction of a single model.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] In one sense, ensemble learning may be thought of as a way to compensate for poor learning algorithms by performing a lot of extra computation.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] On the other hand, the alternative is to do a lot more learning with one non-ensemble model.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] An ensemble may be more efficient at improving overall accuracy for the same increase in compute, storage, or communication resources by using that increase on two or more methods, than would have been improved by increasing resource use for a single method.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Fast algorithms such as decision trees are commonly used in ensemble methods (e.g., random forests), although slower algorithms can benefit from ensemble techniques as well.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] By analogy, ensemble techniques have been used also in unsupervised learning scenarios, for example in consensus clustering or in anomaly detection.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Empirically, ensembles tend to yield better results when there is a significant diversity among the models.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Many ensemble methods, therefore, seek to promote diversity among the models they combine.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Although perhaps non-intuitive, more random algorithms (like random decision trees) can be used to produce a stronger ensemble than very deliberate algorithms (like entropy-reducing decision trees).
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Using a variety of strong learning algorithms, however, has been shown to be more effective than using techniques that attempt to *dumb-down* the models in order to promote diversity.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] It is possible to increase diversity in the training stage of the model using correlation for regression tasks or using information measures such as cross entropy for classification tasks.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Theoretically, one can justify the diversity concept because the lower bound of the error rate of an ensemble system can be decomposed into accuracy, diversity, and the other term.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Ensemble learning, including both regression and classification tasks, can be explained using a geometric framework.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Within this framework, the output of each individual classifier or regressor for the entire dataset can be viewed as a point in a multi-dimensional space.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The Euclidean distance is used as the metric to measure both the performance of a single classifier or regressor (the distance between its point and the ideal point) and the dissimilarity between two classifiers or regressors (the distance between their respective points).
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] This perspective transforms ensemble learning into a deterministic problem.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] For example, within this geometric framework, it can be proved that the averaging of the outputs (scores) of all base classifiers or regressors can lead to equal or better results than the average of all the individual models.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] It can also be proved that if the optimal weighting scheme is used, then a weighted averaging approach can outperform any of the individual classifiers or regressors that make up the ensemble or as good as the best performer at least.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] While the number of component classifiers of an ensemble has a great impact on the accuracy of prediction, there is a limited number of studies addressing this problem.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] *A priori* determining of ensemble size and the volume and velocity of big data streams make this even more crucial for online ensemble classifiers.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Mostly statistical tests were used for determining the proper number of components.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] More recently, a theoretical framework suggested that there is an ideal number of component classifiers for an ensemble such that having more or less than this number of classifiers would deteriorate the accuracy.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] It is called "the law of diminishing returns in ensemble construction." Their theoretical framework shows that using the same number of independent component classifiers as class labels gives the highest accuracy.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The Bayes optimal classifier is a classification technique.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] It is an ensemble of all the hypotheses in the hypothesis space.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] On average, no other ensemble can outperform it.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The Naive Bayes classifier is a version of this that assumes that the data is conditionally independent on the class and makes the computation more feasible.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Each hypothesis is given a vote proportional to the likelihood that the training dataset would be sampled from a system if that hypothesis were true.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] To facilitate training data of finite size, the vote of each hypothesis is also multiplied by the prior probability of that hypothesis.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] where y is the predicted class, C is the set of all possible classes, H is the hypothesis space, P refers to a *probability*, and T is the training data.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] As an ensemble, the Bayes optimal classifier represents a hypothesis that is not necessarily in H .
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The hypothesis represented by the Bayes optimal classifier, however, is the optimal hypothesis in *ensemble space* (the space of all possible ensembles consisting only of hypotheses in H ).
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Bootstrap aggregation (*bagging*) involves training an ensemble on *bootstrapped* data sets.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] A bootstrapped set is created by selecting from original training data set with replacement.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Thus, a bootstrap set may contain a given example zero, one, or multiple times.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Ensemble members can also have limits on the features (e.g., nodes of a decision tree), to encourage exploring of diverse features.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The variance of local information in the bootstrap sets and feature considerations promote diversity in the ensemble, and can strengthen the ensemble.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] To reduce overfitting, a member can be validated using the out-of-bag set (the examples that are not in its bootstrap set).
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Inference is done by **voting** of predictions of ensemble members, called **aggregation**.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] It is illustrated below with an ensemble of four decision trees.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The query example is classified by each tree.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Because three of the four predict the *positive* class, the ensemble's overall classification is *positive*.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Random forests like the one shown are a common application of bagging.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Boosting involves training successive models by emphasizing training data mis-classified by previously learned models.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Initially, all data (D1) has equal weight and is used to learn a base model M1.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The examples mis-classified by M1 are assigned a weight greater than correctly classified examples.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] This boosted data (D2) is used to train a second base model M2, and so on.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] In some cases, boosting has yielded better accuracy than bagging, but tends to over-fit more.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The most common implementation of boosting is Adaboost, but some newer algorithms are reported to achieve better results.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Bayesian model averaging (BMA) makes predictions by averaging the predictions of models weighted by their posterior probabilities given the data.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] BMA is known to generally give better answers than a single model, obtained, e.g., via stepwise regression, especially where very different models have nearly identical performance in the training set but may otherwise perform quite differently.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The question with any use of Bayes' theorem is the prior, i.e., the probability (perhaps subjective) that each model is the best to use for a given purpose.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Conceptually, BMA can be used with any prior.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] *R* packages ensembleBMA and BMA use the prior implied by the Bayesian information criterion, (BIC), following Raftery (1995).
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] *R* package BAS supports the use of the priors implied by Akaike information criterion (AIC) and other criteria over the alternative models as well as priors over the coefficients.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The difference between BIC and AIC is the strength of preference for parsimony.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] BIC's penalty for model complexity is $\ln(n)k$ , while AIC's is $2k$ .
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] On the other hand, AIC and AICc are asymptotically "efficient" (i.e., minimum mean square prediction error), while BIC is not .
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] (1994) showed that when BMA is used for classification, its expected error is at most twice the expected error of the Bayes optimal classifier.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Burnham and Anderson (1998, 2002) contributed greatly to introducing a wider audience to the basic ideas of Bayesian model averaging and popularizing the methodology.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The availability of software, including other free open-source packages for R beyond those mentioned above, helped make the methods accessible to a wider audience.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Bayesian model combination (BMC) is an algorithmic correction to Bayesian model averaging (BMA).
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Instead of sampling each model in the ensemble individually, it samples from the space of possible ensembles (with model weights drawn randomly from a Dirichlet distribution having uniform parameters).
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] This modification overcomes the tendency of BMA to converge toward giving all the weight to a single model.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Although BMC is somewhat more computationally expensive than BMA, it tends to yield dramatically better results.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] BMC has been shown to be better on average (with statistical significance) than BMA and bagging.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Use of Bayes' law to compute model weights requires computing the probability of the data given each model.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Typically, none of the models in the ensemble are exactly the distribution from which the training data were generated, so all of them correctly receive a value close to zero for this term.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] This would work well if the ensemble were big enough to sample the entire model-space, but this is rarely possible.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Consequently, each pattern in the training data will cause the ensemble weight to shift toward the model in the ensemble that is closest to the distribution of the training data.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] It essentially reduces to an unnecessarily complex method for doing model selection.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The possible weightings for an ensemble can be visualized as lying on a simplex.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] At each vertex of the simplex, all of the weight is given to a single model in the ensemble.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] BMA converges toward the vertex that is closest to the distribution of the training data.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] By contrast, BMC converges toward the point where this distribution projects onto the simplex.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] In other words, instead of selecting the one model that is closest to the generating distribution, it seeks the combination of models that is closest to the generating distribution.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The results from BMA can often be approximated by using cross-validation to select the best model from a bucket of models.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Likewise, the results from BMC may be approximated by using cross-validation to select the best ensemble combination from a random sampling of possible weightings.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] A "bucket of models" is an ensemble technique in which a model selection algorithm is used to choose the best model for each problem.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] When tested with only one problem, a bucket of models can produce no better results than the best model in the set, but when evaluated across many problems, it will typically produce much better results, on average, than any model in the set.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The most common approach used for model-selection is cross-validation selection (sometimes called a "bake-off contest").
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Cross-Validation Selection can be summed up as: "try them all with the training set, and pick the one that works best".
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Gating is a generalization of Cross-Validation Selection.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] It involves training another learning model to decide which of the models in the bucket is best-suited to solve the problem.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Often, a perceptron is used for the gating model.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] It can be used to pick the "best" model, or it can be used to give a linear weight to the predictions from each model in the bucket.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] When a bucket of models is used with a large set of problems, it may be desirable to avoid training some of the models that take a long time to train.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Landmark learning is a meta-learning approach that seeks to solve this problem.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] It involves training only the fast (but imprecise) algorithms in the bucket, and then using the performance of these algorithms to help determine which slow (but accurate) algorithm is most likely to do best.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The most common approach for training classifier is using Cross-entropy cost function.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] However, one would like to train an ensemble of models that have diversity so when we combine them it would provide best results.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Assuming we use a simple ensemble of averaging K classifiers.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] where $e^{k}$ is the cost function of the $k^{th}$ classifier, $q^{k}$ is the probability of the $k^{th}$ classifier, p is the true probability that we need to estimate and $\lambda$ is a parameter between 0 and 1 that define the diversity that we would like to establish.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] When $\lambda =0$ we want each classifier to do its best regardless of the ensemble and when $\lambda =1$ we would like the classifier to be as diverse as possible.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Stacking (sometimes called *stacked generalization*) involves training a model to combine the predictions of several other learning algorithms.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] If an arbitrary combiner algorithm is used, then stacking can theoretically represent any of the ensemble techniques described in this article, although, in practice, a logistic regression model is often used as the combiner.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Stacking typically yields performance better than any single one of the trained models.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] It has been successfully used on both supervised learning tasks (regression, classification and distance learning ) and unsupervised learning (density estimation).
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] It has also been used to estimate bagging's error rate.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] It has been reported to out-perform Bayesian model-averaging.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The two top-performers in the Netflix competition utilized blending, which may be considered a form of stacking.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Bayesian predictive stacking generalizes the idea of stacking from the statistical estimation literature to the combination of posterior predictive distributions.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] These ideas have also been developed and investigated for Gaussian process models, especially for spatial data analysis and can be used to construct transfer learning frameworks for massive spatial data sets.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Weighted majority algorithm (machine learning).
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] In recent years, due to growing computational power, which allows for training in large ensemble learning in a reasonable time frame, the number of ensemble learning applications has grown increasingly.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Land cover mapping is one of the major applications of Earth observation satellite sensors, using remote sensing and geospatial data, to identify the materials and objects which are located on the surface of target areas.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Generally, the classes of target materials include roads, buildings, rivers, lakes, and vegetation.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Some different ensemble learning approaches based on artificial neural networks, kernel principal component analysis (KPCA), decision trees with boosting, random forest and automatic design of multiple classifier systems, are proposed to efficiently identify land cover objects.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Change detection is an image analysis problem, consisting of the identification of places where the land cover has changed over time.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Change detection is widely used in fields such as urban growth, forest and vegetation dynamics, land use and disaster monitoring.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The earliest applications of ensemble classifiers in change detection are designed with the majority voting, Bayesian model averaging, and the maximum posterior probability.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Given the growth of satellite data over time, the past decade sees more use of time series methods for continuous change detection from image stacks.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] One example is a Bayesian ensemble changepoint detection method called BEAST, with the software available as a package Rbeast in R, Python, and Matlab.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Distributed denial of service is one of the most threatening cyber-attacks that may happen to an internet service provider.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] By combining the output of single classifiers, ensemble classifiers reduce the total error of detecting and discriminating such attacks from legitimate flash crowds.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Classification of malware codes such as computer viruses, computer worms, trojans, ransomware and spywares with the usage of machine learning techniques, is inspired by the document categorization problem.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Ensemble learning systems have shown a proper efficacy in this area.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Malware detection models, like all machine learning models, are vulnerable to adversarial machine learning attacks where an attacker pushes the boundary of what is classified as malware.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] By rotating through an ensemble of models using moving target defense, the attacker has a diminished knowledge advantage.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] An intrusion detection system monitors computer network or computer systems to identify intruder codes like an anomaly detection process.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Ensemble learning successfully aids such monitoring systems to reduce their total error.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Face recognition, which recently has become one of the most popular research areas of pattern recognition, copes with identification or verification of a person by their digital images.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Hierarchical ensembles based on Gabor Fisher classifier and independent component analysis preprocessing techniques are some of the earliest ensembles employed in this field.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] It is also being successfully used in facial emotion recognition.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Fraud detection deals with the identification of bank fraud, such as money laundering, credit card fraud and telecommunication fraud, which have vast domains of research and applications of machine learning.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Because ensemble learning improves the robustness of the normal behavior modelling, it has been proposed as an efficient technique to detect such fraudulent cases and activities in banking and credit card systems.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Ensemble learning methods have been widely adopted in finance for tasks such as credit scoring, bankruptcy prediction, and risk management.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] By combining multiple base models, ensembles can exploit nonlinear relationships, handle high-dimensional and noisy data, and often deliver more stable out-of-sample performance than single models or traditional statistical baselines such as logistic regression and linear factor models.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] This approach aligns with the broader trend in financial machine learning described by Marcos López de Prado, who argues that combining diverse learners can improve robustness, mitigate overfitting, and extract persistent patterns from noisy financial time series.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] In retail and corporate credit scoring, ensemble classifiers such as random forests, gradient boosting machines and stacked models are frequently used to assess default risk.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Ensemble methods have also been applied to corporate failure and bankruptcy prediction.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Studies comparing different ensemble constructions (such as bagging, boosting and heterogeneous classifier pools) report that well-tuned ensembles tend to achieve higher classification accuracy and more robust performance across industries than individual models.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] The accuracy of prediction of business failure is a very crucial issue in financial decision-making.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Therefore, different ensemble classifiers are proposed to predict financial crises and financial distress.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Also, in the trade-based manipulation problem, where traders attempt to manipulate stock prices by buying and selling activities, ensemble classifiers are required to analyze the changes in the stock market data and detect suspicious symptom of stock price manipulation.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Implementation of ensemble learning not only with machine learning models but also with mathematical frameworks such as hidden Markov models for applications in trading, regime detection, and asset pricing remains a rapidly developing area of research.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Ensemble classifiers have been successfully applied in neuroscience, proteomics and medical diagnosis like in neuro-cognitive disorder (i.e.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Alzheimer or myotonic dystrophy) detection based on MRI datasets, cervical cytology classification.
[src:boosting-theory/ensemble-learning] Besides, ensembles have been successfully applied in medical segmentation tasks, for example brain tumor and hyperintensities segmentation.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] The idea of gradient boosting originated in the observation by Leo Breiman that boosting can be interpreted as an optimization algorithm on a suitable cost function.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Explicit regression gradient boosting algorithms were subsequently developed, by Jerome H.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Friedman, (in 1999 and later in 2001) simultaneously with the more general functional gradient boosting perspective of Llew Mason, Jonathan Baxter, Peter Bartlett and Marcus Frean.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] The latter two papers introduced the view of boosting algorithms as iterative *functional gradient descent* algorithms.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] That is, algorithms that optimize a cost function over function space by iteratively choosing a function (weak hypothesis) that points in the negative gradient direction.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] This functional gradient view of boosting has led to the development of boosting algorithms in many areas of machine learning and statistics beyond regression and classification.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Like other boosting methods, gradient boosting combines weak "learners" into a single strong learner iteratively.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] If the algorithm has M stages, at each stage m ( $1\leq m\leq M$ ), suppose some imperfect model $F_{m}$ (for low m , this model may simply predict ${\hat {y}}_{i}$ to be ${\bar {y}}$ , the mean of y ).
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] In order to improve $F_{m}$ , our algorithm should add some new estimator, $h_{m}(x)$ .
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Therefore, gradient boosting will fit $h_{m}$ to the *residual* $y_{i}-F_{m}(x_{i})$ .
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] As in other boosting variants, each $F_{m+1}$ attempts to correct the errors of its predecessor $F_{m}$ .
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] So, gradient boosting could be generalized to a gradient descent algorithm by plugging in a different loss and its gradient.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Many supervised learning problems involve an output variable y and a vector of input variables x, related to each other with some probabilistic distribution.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] The goal is to find some function ${\hat {F}}(x)$ that best approximates the output variable from the values of input variables.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] The gradient boosting method assumes a real-valued y.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] where $\gamma _{m}$ is the weight at stage m .
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] We are usually given a training set $\{(x_{1},y_{1}),\dots ,(x_{n},y_{n})\}$ of known values of x and corresponding values of y.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] In accordance with the empirical risk minimization principle, the method tries to find an approximation ${\hat {F}}(x)$ that minimizes the average value of the loss function on the training set, i.e., minimizes the empirical risk.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] for $m\geq 1$ , where $h_{m}\in {\mathcal {H}}$ is a base learner function.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Unfortunately, choosing the best function $h_{m}$ at each step for an arbitrary loss function L is a computationally infeasible optimization problem in general.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Therefore, we restrict our approach to a simplified version of the problem.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] The idea is to apply a steepest descent step to this minimization problem (functional gradient descent).
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] The basic idea is to find a local minimum of the loss function by iterating on $F_{m-1}(x)$ .
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] In fact, the local maximum-descent direction of the loss function is the negative gradient.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Note that this approach is a heuristic and therefore doesn't yield an exact solution to the given problem, but rather an approximation.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Fit a base learner (or weak learner, e.g. tree) closed under scaling $h_{m}(x)$ to pseudo-residuals, i.e. train it using the training set $\{(x_{i},r_{im})\}_{i=1}^{n}$ .
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Gradient boosting is typically used with decision trees (especially CARTs) of a fixed size as base learners.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] For this special case, Friedman proposes a modification to gradient boosting method which improves the quality of fit of each base learner.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Generic gradient boosting at the *m*-th step would fit a decision tree $h_{m}(x)$ to pseudo-residuals.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Let $J_{m}$ be the number of its leaves.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] The tree partitions the input space into $J_{m}$ disjoint regions $R_{1m},\ldots ,R_{J_{m}m}$ and predicts a constant value in each region.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] where $b_{jm}$ is the value predicted in the region $R_{jm}$ .
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Friedman proposes to modify this algorithm so that it chooses a separate optimal value $\gamma _{jm}$ for each of the tree's regions, instead of a single $\gamma _{m}$ for the whole tree.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] He calls the modified algorithm "TreeBoost".
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] When the loss $L(\cdot ,\cdot )$ is mean-squared error (MSE) the coefficients $\gamma _{jm}$ coincide with the coefficients of the tree-fitting procedure $b_{jm}$ .
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] The number J of terminal nodes in the trees is a parameter which controls the maximum allowed level of interaction between variables in the model.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] With $J=2$ (decision stumps), no interaction between variables is allowed.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] With $J=3$ the model may include effects of the interaction between up to two variables, and so on.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] J can be adjusted for a data set at hand.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Hastie et al. comment that typically $4\leq J\leq 8$ work well for boosting and results are fairly insensitive to the choice of J in this range, $J=2$ is insufficient for many applications, and $J>10$ is unlikely to be required.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Fitting the training set too closely can lead to degradation of the model's generalization ability, that is, its performance on unseen examples.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Several so-called regularization techniques reduce this overfitting effect by constraining the fitting procedure.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] One natural regularization parameter is the number of gradient boosting iterations *M* (i.e. the number of base models).
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Increasing *M* reduces the error on training set, but increases risk of overfitting.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] An optimal value of *M* is often selected by monitoring prediction error on a separate validation data set.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Another regularization parameter for tree boosting is tree depth.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] The higher this value the more likely the model will overfit the training data.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] where parameter $\nu$ is called the "learning rate".
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Empirically, it has been found that using small learning rates (such as $\nu <0.1$ ) yields dramatic improvements in models' generalization ability over gradient boosting without shrinking ( $\nu =1$ ).
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] However, it comes at the price of increasing computational time both during training and querying: lower learning rate requires more iterations.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Soon after the introduction of gradient boosting, Friedman proposed a minor modification to the algorithm, motivated by Breiman's bootstrap aggregation ("bagging") method.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Specifically, he proposed that at each iteration of the algorithm, a base learner should be fit on a subsample of the training set drawn at random without replacement.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Friedman observed a substantial improvement in gradient boosting's accuracy with this modification.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Subsample size is some constant fraction f of the size of the training set.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] When $f=1$ , the algorithm is deterministic and identical to the one described above.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Smaller values of f introduce randomness into the algorithm and help prevent overfitting, acting as a kind of regularization.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] The algorithm also becomes faster, because regression trees have to be fit to smaller datasets at each iteration.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Friedman obtained that $0.5\leq f\leq 0.8$ leads to good results for small and moderate sized training sets.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Therefore, f is typically set to 0.5, meaning that one half of the training set is used to build each base learner.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Also, like in bagging, subsampling allows one to define an out-of-bag error of the prediction performance improvement by evaluating predictions on those observations which were not used in the building of the next base learner.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Out-of-bag estimates help avoid the need for an independent validation dataset, but often underestimate actual performance improvement and the optimal number of iterations.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Gradient tree boosting implementations often also use regularization by limiting the minimum number of observations in trees' terminal nodes.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] It is used in the tree building process by ignoring any splits that lead to nodes containing fewer than this number of training set instances.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Imposing this limit helps to reduce variance in predictions at leaves.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Another useful regularization technique for gradient boosted model is to penalize its complexity.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] For gradient boosted trees, model complexity can be defined as the proportional number of leaves in the trees.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] The joint optimization of loss and model complexity corresponds to a post-pruning algorithm to remove branches that fail to reduce the loss by a threshold.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Other kinds of regularization such as an $\ell _{2}$ penalty on the leaf values can also be used to avoid overfitting.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Gradient boosting can be used in the field of learning to rank.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] The commercial web search engines Yahoo and Yandex use variants of gradient boosting in their machine-learned ranking engines.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Gradient boosting is also utilized in High Energy Physics in data analysis.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] At the Large Hadron Collider (LHC), variants of gradient boosting Deep Neural Networks (DNN) were successful in reproducing the results of non-machine learning methods of analysis on datasets used to discover the Higgs boson.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Gradient boosting decision tree was also applied in earth and geological studies – for example quality evaluation of sandstone reservoir.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Friedman introduced his regression technique as a "Gradient Boosting Machine" (GBM).
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Mason, Baxter et al. described the generalized abstract class of algorithms as "functional gradient boosting".
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Friedman et al. describe an advancement of gradient boosted models as Multiple Additive Regression Trees (MART); Elith et al. describe that approach as "Boosted Regression Trees" (BRT).
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] A popular open-source implementation for R calls it a "Generalized Boosting Model", however packages expanding this work use BRT.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Yet another name is TreeNet, after an early commercial implementation from Salford System's Dan Steinberg, one of researchers who pioneered the use of tree-based methods.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Gradient boosting can be used for feature importance ranking, which is usually based on aggregating importance function of the base learners.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] For example, if a gradient boosted trees algorithm is developed using entropy-based decision trees, the ensemble algorithm ranks the importance of features based on entropy as well with the caveat that it is averaged out over all base learners.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] While boosting can increase the accuracy of a base learner, such as a decision tree or linear regression, it sacrifices intelligibility and interpretability.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] For example, following the path that a decision tree takes to make its decision is trivial and self-explained, but following the paths of hundreds or thousands of trees is much harder.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] To achieve both performance and interpretability, some model compression techniques allow transforming an XGBoost into a single "born-again" decision tree that approximates the same decision function.
[src:boosting-theory/gradient-boosting] Furthermore, its implementation may be more difficult due to the higher computational demand.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] In machine learning (ML), a **margin classifier** is a type of classification model which is able to give an associated distance from the decision boundary for each data sample.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] For instance, if a linear classifier is used, the distance (typically Euclidean, though others may be used) of a sample from the separating hyperplane is the margin of that sample.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] The notion of *margins* is important in several ML classification algorithms, as it can be used to bound the generalization error of these classifiers.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] These bounds are frequently shown using the VC dimension.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] The generalization error bound in boosting algorithms and support vector machines is particularly prominent.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] The margin for an iterative boosting algorithm given a dataset with two classes can be defined as follows: the classifier is given a sample pair $(x,y)$ , where $x\in X$ is a domain space and $y\in Y=\{-1,+1\}$ is the sample's label.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] The algorithm then selects a classifier $h_{j}\in C$ at each iteration j where C is a space of possible classifiers that predict real values.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] This hypothesis is then weighted by $\alpha _{j}\in R$ as selected by the boosting algorithm.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] By this definition, the margin is positive if the sample is labeled correctly, or negative if the sample is labeled incorrectly.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] This definition may be modified and is not the only way to define the margin for boosting algorithms.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] However, there are reasons why this definition may be appealing.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] Many classifiers can give an associated margin for each sample.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] However, only some classifiers utilize information of the margin while learning from a dataset.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] Many boosting algorithms rely on the notion of a margin to assign weight to samples.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] If a convex loss is utilized (as in AdaBoost or LogitBoost, for instance) then a sample with a higher margin will receive less (or equal) weight than a sample with a lower margin.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] This leads the boosting algorithm to focus weight on low-margin samples.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] In non-convex algorithms (e.g., BrownBoost), the margin still dictates the weighting of a sample, though the weighting is non-monotone with respect to the margin.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] One theoretical motivation behind margin classifiers is that their generalization error may be bound by the algorithm parameters and a margin term.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] An example of such a bound is for the AdaBoost algorithm.
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] Let S be a set of m data points, sampled independently at random from a distribution D .
[src:boosting-theory/margin-classifier] Assume the VC-dimension of the underlying base classifier is d and $m\geq d\geq 1$ .
